@database "References Guide"
@author "Heiko Schr—der"
@$VER: 3.0 (Release 3)
@wordwrap

@node Main "References"
                               @{" < Table of content " link "Macro-Package.guide/Main"}

         !!! This macro only functions with £Final Writer 5¨ and above !!!

@{fg shine}Benifits:@{fg text}
   You write a document and cover something in a different text passage an
   other page (eg. with "see page y"). First you must complete your document
   (Delete Text boxes, corrections etc.). Now you can not remember, where
   that piece of text was on the other page.

   Before you had to write your "see page" references by hand. With larger
   documents and greater quantities of text this takes a long time.

   These times are past. Now you have the Reference Assistent to automatically
   this work for you.

@{fg shine}Requirements:@{fg text}
   £Final Writer 5¨ or later
   The text must not be in Text frames.

@{fg shine}Using the @{"macro" system "Sys:Utilities/Multiview Reference.iff"}:@{fg text}

   Set Ref. @{fg fill}n@{fg text}ame
      To set a reference you must first select an obvious name to call this
      piece of text. At the start this is the only button available.

      Highlight the text, you wish to draw a reference to.
      Then push the button.

      The Field "Ref. name" will activate.
      Here you put the obvious name for this piece of text.
      With £ENTER¨ you give the text its new name.
      If this field is empty and you press £ENTER¨ you cancel the attempt to
      set that reference.

      If you have given a text, a section will appear, in this section the
      information to create the references will be stored.
      This section is called @{fg shine}Reference@{fg text}.
      Please do not type in this section. If you do there is NO GUARANTEE that
      the correct references will be given.

      After the marked text a character will be written, this is for the
      Assistant, and you should not be able to see it.(Width: 4, Colour: White).

   @{fg fill}D@{fg text}elete ref. name
      The macro through searches the document to find all the reference names
      and the gives a list.
      Choose the name to delete from the list. All references to this text will
      now be erased.

      The list can be closed with the "ESC" key or by choosing a name to
      delete.

   @{fg fill}S@{fg text}et reference
      Position the cursor where you wish the reference to be placed, then press
      this button. The macro now searches through the document to find all of
      the reference names and gives a list.
      
      The list can be closed with the "ESC" or by setting a reference.

      If you have chosen a reference name , the references will appear in the
      document. The overview is set through the next field.

   @{fg fill}F@{fg text}ormat:
      Here you set the format for your reference.
      %A = Symbol for the Section name
      %K = Symbol for the Chapter name
      %S = Symbol for the Page number

      !!! Please don't use quotation marks. !!!

      A few examples:
                     (See %K, page %S)
         Example 1:  (See Introduction, Page 2)

                     (See Chapter: %K, p.%S)
         Example 2:  (See Chapter: Introduction, p.2)

                     => Section: %A, p. %S
         Example 3:  => Section: Main, p. 2

   @{fg fill}R@{fg text}efresh references
      If you have modified the text you can use this to up date the references.

   Cre@{fg fill}a@{fg text}te references
      If you choose this function, a requester will ask you if you wish to
      continue.

      This button should be the last thing you do..

      First, the macro will search for all of the references, and update them.
      Then all of the special characters will be deleted. If this works the
      document should be saved with the ending ".VW".

      If you want to change the text you should use the previously saved file
      which still contains the references, and not the file with the ".VW"
      extension, as all references have been deleted. Then create the
      references again when you have finished.

                     - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - 

   @{fg fill}ESC@{fg text} or closing the window
      terminates the macro.

                     - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - 

@{fg shine}Hint:@{fg text}
      If it gives problems, the macro refuses to start or something similar.
      Then delete  the preferences file:
         "S:FW_references.prefs".
      This should aliviate most problems.

@{fg shine}WARNING:@{fg text}
      If you write a document with the characters @{fg shine}"Þ" or "Ì"@{fg text}
      in it the reference manager may throw up some extra reference names.
      So please IGNORE the extra references.
      These characters are VERY IMPORTANT for the reference manager and should
      be avoided as the assistant could automatically delete them.

@endnode
